'Any owner could try to re-spend an already spent coin by signing it again to another owner. The usual solution is for a trusted company with a central database to check for double-spending, but that just gets back to the trust model. In its central position, the company can override the users, and the fees needed to support the company make micropayments impractical. 
Bitcoin's solution is to use a peer-to-peer network to check for double-spending. In a nutshell, the network works like a distributed timestamp server, stamping the first transaction to spend a coin. It takes advantage of the nature of information being easy to spread but hard to stifle.' February 11, 2009 - Satoshi Nakamoto

Daily Inspiration: "You don't need a motivational speaker. You just need a motivational future!" - Futurist Jim Carroll

When people ask me what I do for a living, I will often offer up that I'm a speaker - after all, sometimes it's hard to explain what a 'futurist' does. The question inevitably comes back, "Oh, are you a motivational speaker?" To which I respond, "Not really." Â This leads to a rather quizzical look.

Am I a motivational speaker? Not at all, I guess. I will note that I think I can be pretty inspirational and motivational on stage. I have never quite understood why people need a 'motivational' speaker. Isn't knowing about the wonders of tomorrow good enough to get you going?

Ah, motivational speakers. it's certainly a world very different from what I do. 

Have I told you about the office of Tony Robbins? They reached out to me. Tony, of course, is the most motivational of all the motivational speakers out there. His team asked if I might fly to Miami to participate in one of his 'Power Within' events. 

Sure, I wrote back in an email; here's my fee. They never responded. I took a look at the Website for the event and saw that he was charging about $10,000 for people to attend. He's probably pretty motivated with fees like that, particularly if he can get others to help him out in some sort of motivational serfdom.

 I wasn't very motivated to help him earn that $10,000 by working for free, LOL.

**Prisons Dept welcomes university cooperation to enhance well-being of inmates**



**KAJANG**: The Prisons Department welcomes cooperation from local universities in the effort to enhance the well-being of prison inmates through education programmes and initiatives to improve the facilities for the children of the inmates.

Its deputy commissioner general (Management) Abd Kadir Rais said this is because inmate rehabilitation process inside and outside the prison walls requires the involvement of the community.

â€œTherefore, the cooperation of all parties including government agencies, the private sector, government-linked companies, non-governmental agencies and the community is crucial in supporting and helping to provide job opportunities to inmates,â€ he told Bernama.

Abd Kadir said this after the handover ceremony of the Cradle For Inclusive Nurturing and Teaching Atmosphere project (C.I.N.T.A CARE) at Kajang Womenâ€™s Prison, here, today.

Also present, Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia (UKM) Prof Emeritus Datuk Dr Mohamad Abd Razak.

The project involves upgrading the facilities for children of inmates in collaboration with UKM Alumni Relations Centre.

According to Abd Kadir, the C.I.N.T.A CARE project has a huge impact on the well-being and development of children born in prisons because a conducive environment and appropriate equipment provide opportunities for the children to grow optimally.

For the record, there are five children living in the prison, comprising two girls and three boys, aged between two and three years old.

Meanwhile, Dr Mohamad said the C.I.N.T.A CARE is the first of its kind to be conducted by UKM in collaboration with the Prisons Department, adding that the university is ready to carry out other programmes with the department including providing medical treatment and education for these children. - _Bernama_

**Dr Mohd Mazri, Zulkifli diumum calon PN PRK Simpang Jeram, Pulai**



**JOHOR BAHRU**: Pakar perunding vaskular dan pakar bedah endovaskular Dr Mohd Mazri Yahya dan ahli perniagaan Zulkifli Jaafar, masing-masing dinamakan sebagai calon Perikatan Nasional (PN) bagi Pilihan Raya Kecil (PRK) Dewan Undangan Negeri (DUN) Simpang Jeram dan Parlimen Pulai.

Pengerusi PN Tan Sri Muhyiddin Yassin yang mengumumkan perkara itu berkata pemilihan kedua-dua calon itu dimuktamadkan setelah mengambil kira semua faktor dan pandangan parti-parti dalam PN.

â€œKedua-dua parti, Bersatu dan PAS, ada jawatankuasa yang membuat penilaian berdasarkan beberapa kriteria seperti kelayakan, pengalaman, sifat, kegiatan dan lain-lain.

â€œIa bukan diputuskan seorang, PAS ada sistem, Bersatu ada sistem (untuk menilai) selepas (peringkat) bahagian dan kawasan menamakan beberapa nama yang sesuai. Kita putuskan hanya seorang bagi kawasan yang ditandingi,â€ kata Presiden Bersatu itu kepada pemberita selepas majlis pengumuman calon PN bagi kedua-dua kerusi itu di sini hari ini.

Beliau berkata Dr Mohd Mazri dan Zulkifli merupakan pemimpin kawasan serta calon yang berwibawa dan berintegriti.

Dr Mazri, 54, Ahli Jawatankuasa PAS Pusat dan bekas Timbalan Pesuruhjaya PAS Johor, pernah bertanding di DUN Simpang Jeram dan Parlimen Pulai pada Pilihan Raya Umum ke-14.

Timbalan Ketua Bahagian Bersatu Pulai Zulkifli, 50, yang mempunyai 26 tahun pengalaman sebagai ahli perniagaan dalam bidang logistik dan pengangkutan pula merupakan calon muka baharu.

Muhyiddin yang juga Presiden Bersatu berkata PN tidak menawarkan manifesto khusus untuk PRK berkenaan tetapi akan menjelaskan kaedah PN dalam menangani isu-isu khusus yang dialami rakyat Johor, misalnya dalam soal kemiskinan dan isu kos sara hidup. _-Bernama_

**Coach: Speedy Tigers in crucial phase of preparation towards Asiad dream**



**KUALA LUMPUR**: The national menâ€™s hockey team is now in the most crucial phase of preparation ahead of the 2022 Asian Games in Hangzhou, China, scheduled from Sept 23 to Oct 8.

With eyes on the gold medal to secure a 2024 Paris Olympic slot, the Speedy Tigers cannot afford to slip again when facing the best of Asia at the Gongshu Canal Sports Park, after being stunned by dark horses Japan in the 2018 Jakarta-Palembang Asian Games finals.

For head coach A. Arulselvaraj _(pix)_, the focus is now on the finer details involving penalty corners and technical aspects of the game that need to be rectified before leaving to Hangzhou.

â€œThe focus will be on little things like ball speed and penalty corners, the very basic fundamental stuff. We will also have an empowerment week where we will be continuing with gym and fitness training, but stay away from hockey as part of our preparation plan,â€ he told Bernama.

The Speedy Tigers also managed to get back the services of former Australian internationals Kieren Govers and Glen Turner to help strengthen the squadâ€™s goalscoring and penalty corner strikes for a week.

Talking on the main challengers for the Asiad gold, Arulselvaraj said the recent Asian Champions Trophy (ACT) 2023 in India, gave the team a good outlook on the opponents.

â€œOff course we donâ€™t know howâ€™s their preparations like towards the Asian Games, but we got to play all the nations there. So we take note and analyse what they can do and canâ€™t do.

â€œIt is better as we gained the details based on how we played against them, rather than watching them playing against other teams. A good outcome,â€ he said.

Arulselvaraj, who was named best male coach of the year at the 2022 National Sports Award recently, led the Speedy Tigers to their best ever performance to finish runners up behind India in the ACT.

The Speedy Tigers are expected to depart for Hangzhou on Sept 20, four days before their first Group B match against Thailand.

He said the team had no plans to leave early as the weather conditions and time zone is similar to home, while food shouldnâ€™t be an issue as multiple cuisines would be served at the Games Village.

South Korea, Oman, Indonesia and hosts China are other challengers in the group, while world number three India, defending champion Japan, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Singapore and Uzbekistan make up Group A. - _Bernama_

Most people often confuse two important concepts: price inflation and monetary inflation.

When it comes to #Bitcoin, it serves as a hedge against the latter, the more subtle yet more dangerous form. Monetary inflation occurs when central banks increase the money supply, leading to a devaluation of the monetary unit and a decline in its purchasing power. This type of inflation triggers a universal increase in prices, as opposed to price inflation, which tends to affect specific products or services.

By design, Bitcoin maintains an unalterable supply, impervious to modification. This unique feature positions it as a perfect hedge against monetary #inflation.

**MCMC: Kerajaan tidak pernah buat ketetapan naikkan umur persaraan kepada 65 tahun**



**KUALA LUMPUR**: Kerajaan tidak pernah membuat sebarang ketetapan menaikkan umur persaraan kepada 65 tahun sebagaimana tular menerusi media sosial baru-baru ini.

Suruhanjaya Komunikasi dan Multimedia Malaysia (MCMC) memaklumkan penelitian pihaknya mendapati perkara itu ditularkan berdasarkan artikel sebuah akhbar tempatan bertarikh 11 April lepas yang memetik pandangan seorang profesor.

â€œIa hanya pandangan seorang profesor dan bukannya kenyataan rasmi kerajaan,â€œ menurut MCMC melalui portal sebenarnya.my.

Artikel yang diterbitkan kira-kira empat bulan lepas itu mendakwa bahawa Pasaran Buruh Masa Hadapan (EU-ERA) menjangkakan had usia persaraan Malaysia akan dinaikkan daripada 60 ke 65 tahun dalam tempoh beberapa tahun akan datang.

Menurut artikel itu, persaraan wajib di Malaysia yang ditetapkan pada usia 60 tahun secara relatifnya lebih rendah berbanding negara lain, contohnya di Jepun yang ditetapkan pada umur 65 tahun. - _Bernama_

**Kebakaran hutan di Hawaii: 1,100 penduduk masih belum dapat dikesan**



**MOSCOW**: Seramai 1,100 orang masih hilang dalam kebakaran hutan luar biasa yang melanda Pulau Maui di Hawaii baru-baru ini, lapor Sputnik memetik pihak berkuasa.

â€œAntara 1,000 dan 1,100 individu masih tidak dapat dikesan, manakala lebih 1,400 lagi yang pada asalnya dilaporkan hilang telah ditemukan selamat,â€œ kata pihak berkuasa dalam satu kenyataan pada Selasa.

Pihak berkuasa sedang bekerjasama dengan keluarga mangsa yang hilang untuk mengumpul sampel DNA bagi memudahkan proses pengecaman.

Sementara itu, pendakwa negeri Andrew Martin berkata pihaknya akan memastikan bahawa pemberian sampel DNA itu hanya akan digunakan untuk tujuan pengecaman.

Pada Isnin, Datuk Bandar Maui County Richard Bissen berkata sekurang-kurangnya 114 orang maut dan kira-kira 850 lagi hilang dalam kebakaran hutan itu.

Kebakaran itu berlaku akibat cuaca kering dan panas yang diburukkan lagi dengan angin kencang yang dicetuskan oleh Taufan Dora.

Beberapa penempatan, termasuk bandar pelancongan terkenal, Lahaina, musnah dalam kejadian itu. - _Bernama_

**Pengerusi YBK: Aktifkan semula cadangan â€˜kelab satu peratusâ€™ basmi miskin tegar**



**PETALING JAYA**: Kerajaan disaran mengaktifkan semula cadangan mewujudkan â€˜kelab satu peratusâ€™ sebagai ikhtiar membasmi kemiskinan tegar di negara ini, kata Pengerusi Yayasan Basmi Kemiskinan (YBK) Datuk Zainal Abidin Sakom.

Beliau berkata saranan tersebut merupakan antara resolusi yang dicapai menerusi Sidang Meja Bulat Menoktahkan Kemiskinan: Peranan Sektor Ketiga yang diadakan hari ini.

Katanya cadangan tersebut telah dipersetujui Perdana Menteri Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim pada 1996 semasa beliau memegang jawatan Menteri Kewangan, namun pelaksanaannya tidak dapat diteruskan pada ketika itu.

â€œIkhtiar membasmi kemiskinan ini memerlukan dana yang besar, jadi kita mencadangkan sinergi antara pemain sektor swasta dalam menyumbangkan dana secara kolektif bagi tujuan mendapatkan pendanaan untuk inisiatif menoktahkan kemiskinan.

â€œSyarikat berkaitan kerajaan (GLC) dan syarikat luar negara yang beroperasi di Malaysia ini, kita akan minta mereka meletakkan satu peratus daripada keuntungan ke dalam satu tabung yang dijaga kerajaan dan dengan itu semua badan bukan kerajaan (NGO) atau persatuan yang ingin berusaha membasmi kemiskinan, mereka (kerajaan) boleh memberikan dana berkenaan,â€ katanya.

Beliau berkata demikian pada sidang media selepas sidang meja bulat tersebut berakhir di ibu pejabat YBK di sini, hari ini.

Menurutnya lagi cadangan tersebut satu pendekatan yang boleh dilaksanakan oleh kerajaan bagi menunjukkan penglibatan usahawan dalam usaha untuk membasmi kemiskinan tegar.

Menurut YBK berdasarkan rekod ketika ini terdapat kira-kira 118,000 orang miskin tegar di negara ini.

Dalam pada itu, 14 resolusi berjaya dicapai pada sidang meja bulat tersebut yang disertai wakil daripada 50 organisasi termasuk Lembaga Zakat Selangor, NGO dan ahli akademik.

Zainal Abidin berkata kesemua resolusi itu akan dibentangkan dalam satu konvensyen sempena Hari Pembasmian Kemiskinan Sedunia pada 17 Okt ini di Pusat Konvensyen Movenpick KLIA. - _Bernama_

**MCMC: Govt never decided to raise retirement age to 65**



**KUALA LUMPUR**: The government has never made any decision to raise the retirement age to 65 as has gone viral on social media recently.

Malaysian Communications and Multimedia Commission (MCMC) said that based on its observation, the matter was made viral based on a local newspaper article dated April 11, which quoted the views of a professor.

â€œIt was only the views of a professor and not an official statement by the government,â€ the MCMC said through its portal sebenarnya.my.

The article, published about four months ago, claimed that the Future Labour Market (EU-ERA) forecast the retirement age in Malaysia would be increased from 60 to 65 within the next few years.

According to the article, the mandatory retirement age in Malaysia that has been set at 60 was relatively lower compared to other countries, like Japan which has set its retirement age at 65. - _Bernama_

I don't care how slick the client is, if they're dishonest and opaque I'm not going to engage with it.

I think we are mostly in agreement. 

While there are elements of the left and right that I agree with, perhaps more with the right nowadays, I lean libertarian and generally reject siding with either idealogues. 

I still agree with the sentiment of his song, it's hard not to, but I think the context in which diversity is used today is generally something I don't align with. It's another term that has largely been coopted by globalists to continue with their destructive agendas. I think we should pay attention to the words people use, particularly when they are being broadcast by the media. 'Unifying' over this kind of language isn't something I can get behind. Cultures should be preserved instead of being attacked. I do not believe that diversity is a strength, in the way it is portrayed as Western and European culture is bad while all others should be celebrated.

For example, the UK is by default an Anglo culture, yet all we ever hear via the mainstream is how there are too many white people and a lack of representation of other cultures in sport, politics, etc. The mayor of London recently made comments that 'white families' are not representative of London, and there are too many white men on the Transport for London board. The irony of a Muslim man who is the mayor of London making these comments is too much for me. 

This is of course ridiculous when viewed in the context of any other nation, nor is it true in the UK itself. Diversity is only ever an issue when there is a white majority, even when that is the default culture in a nation.

But we aren't allowed nuance in conversation anymore, which I consider tragic for everyone since people take up hard positions aligning with one side or the other.
